subSection.paragraph:
Sucrose (β- D-fructofuranosyl α- D-glucopyranoside) (
Fig. 1
) is a soluble carbohydrate with an estimated production of about 180 million tons per year, with a high degree of purity (> 99%), low production cost (
Eggleston, 2010
; 
Polat and Linhardt, 2001
), and is mostly used as a sweetener. It is considered a raw material for many products such as emulsifiers, synthetic sweeteners, hydrophilic polymers and antimicrobial drugs.

Sucrose may undergo many chemical reactions, with the most exploited ones being esterification with fatty acids (
Gumel et al., 2011
), etherification (
Ohkawabata et al., 2012
; 
Sauthier et al., 2014
) and halogenation (
Erickson and Fields, 2014
; 
Tachrim et al., 2016
). Sucrose esters (SEs) are among the major classes of compounds obtained from sucrose, with many examples of aliphatic and phenylpropanoid substituent groups obtained by transesterification reactions (
Deshpande et al., 2013
; 
Ferrer et al., 2000
; 
Petkova et al., 2015
; 
Polat and Linhardt, 2001
; 
Richel et al., 2011
), biocatalysis (
Khan and Rathod, 2015
; 
Neta et al., 2012
; 
Pérez et al., 2017
; 
Zhao et al., 2015
; 
Zheng et al., 2015
), and reaction with acid halides (
Thévenet et al., 1999
). The control of sucrose reactivity is not an easy task due to its thermal decomposition at 150 ̊ 
C
(caramelization), as well as, hydrolysis under acidic conditions which often yields glucose and fructose. Also, the sucrose polyfunctionality, which arises from the eight hydroxyl groups, makes the synthesis of sucrose derivatives a herculean task, as it is difficult to control the degree of substitution in these functional groups (
Lu et al., 2017
; 
Peris, 2016
; 
Queneau et al., 2007a
, 
2004
).

Besides the synthetic SEs, natural sucrose esters (NSEs) can be obtained from fruits, leaves and other parts of a large number of medicinal plants. In recent years, uncharacterized SEs have been identified from several classes of plants with different biological properties (
El Sheikha et al., 2008
; 
Pérez-Castorena et al., 2012
).

NSEs are found in a large number of plant genera such as 

Nicotiana

(
Neal et al., 1994
; 
Zhu et al., 2013
); 

Lycopersicon

(
Schilmiller et al., 2012
); 

Solanum

(Hali 
ń
ski and 
Stepnowski, 2016
); 

Physalis
(
Bernal et al., 2018
)

; 

Petunia
(
Chortyk et al., 1997
)

, among others, which are used as the traditional medicines for treatment of diseases in different countries because to their anti-inflammatory (
Wang et al., 2003
), antitumor (
Zhao et al., 2013
), antioxidant (
Tian et al., 2004
) and antimicrobial (
Sato et al., 2000
) properties.

(
Gumel et al., 2011
; 
Ocampo et al., 2017
), with their physicochemical and biological properties depending on the degree of esterification, and the 
type
of substituent group present. On this perspective, SEs and NSEs have been utilized in pharmaceutical formulations (
Zheng et al., 2015
); as food emulsifiers (
Scientific Panel on Food Additives, Flavourings, 2004
; 
Shah et al., 2017
), as low-caloric fat substitutes (
Rolls et al., 1992
), in cosmetics production (
Ahsan et al., 2003
), and as inhibitors of Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria (
Ferrer et al., 2005
; 
Mora Vargas et al., 2020
; 
Zhao et al., 2015
). In addition, SEs can be polymerized to produce superporous hydrogels (sucrogels) (
Chen and Park, 2000
).

The lower yield of NSEs makes their extraction and large-scale production almost unfeasible, which underlines the need for the development of synthetic methods for SEs. However, the low stability of sucrose at high temperatures and acidic medium, in addition to its functional richness (eight hydroxyl groups) and structural and electronic considerations, must be taken into account for the development of SEs synthesis methodologies. The main challenge in the synthesis of SEs is the control of the degree of esterification, as well as, the specific hydroxyl group to be substituted in the process, which determines the overall acidity and regioselectively of the desired product (
Davies and Christofides, 1987
; 
Molinier et al., 2003
; 
Queneau et al., 2007a
; 
Thévenet et al., 1999
, 
1997
).

Spectroscopic studies have shown that the C-2- 
OH
on glucose is the most acidic between the eight hydroxyl groups due to the formation of a hydrogen bond with C-3′- 
OH
. In addition, C-1′- 
OH
on fructose in highly polar solvents makes this position the more selective hydroxyl group in substitution reactions (
Bernet and Vasella, 2000
; 
Davies and Christofides, 1987
; 
Queneau et al., 2007a
). However, other effects like intermolecular transesterification and intramolecular migration of the electrophilic species must be taken into account. On this perspective, the regioselectivity and the degree of substitution of the final products can be controlled by distinct physicochemical conditions such as solvent (organic or aqueous), catalysts, temperature of reaction, molar ratio of the starting reagents, and nature of the electrophilic species. Also, the thermodynamic and kinetic reaction effects play an important role in the synthesis process (
Molinier et al., 2003
; 
Queneau et al., 2007a
; 
Thévenet et al., 1999
). Moreover, the use of catalysts for the transesterification reaction in the synthesis of SEs is necessary. The nature of the catalyst (homogenous, heterogeneous or biocatalytic) employed is an important determinant of the yield, selectivity and degree of substitution of the synthetized SEs.

Homogeneous basic catalysis in polar anhydrous medium using dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) or dimethylformamide (DMF) as solvents is the most explored route for the synthesis of SEs (
Molinier et al., 2003
; 
Polat and Linhardt, 2001
; 
Queneau et al., 2007a
). This is based on the principle of reaction of an alcohol (sucrose) with methyl ester of the acid of interest to be esterified to the structure of the molecule (
Queneau et al., 2007b
). Under polar and anhydrous conditions, the catalyst used has a strong alkaline character that enables it to dehydrate the hydroxyl of sucrose.

Other methodology employed in the synthesis of SEs is the protected-unprotected reaction of the hydroxyl groups with acetic anhydride, aldehydes or acetyl halides in the presence of catalysts derived from Lewis bases (
Richel et al., 2011
). The synthesis of SEs by the protection of seven hydroxyl groups via reaction of the sucrose with benzyl groups, and unprotecting the hydroxyl at the OH-6’ position of the molecule was studied. Once the sucrose was protected and unprotected, the product obtained by the transesterification reaction with methyl methacrylate was α, β- unsaturated sucrose with high selectivity and yields (
Fig. 2a
) (
Barros et al., 2010
; 
Barros and Petrova, 2009
).

Biocatalysts has also been employed for the production of SEs, with the main advantage of high specificity and selectivity in the degree of substitutions in the products formed (
Fig. 2b
). Lipases extracted from 

Thermomyces lanuginosus
(
Ferrer et al., 2005
)

and 

Candida antarctica
B

(
Neta et al., 2012
; 
Zhao et al., 2015
), in addition to alkaline proteases 

from 
Bacillus pseudofirmus

AL-89 (
Pedersen et al., 2003
; 
Potier et al., 2001
), have been reported as biocatalysts in the production of SEs with high selectivity for OH-6 and OH-6′ hydroxyl in sucrose by lipases, and high selectivity for OH-1′ hydroxyl in sucrose by proteases. However, the use of biocatalysts is restricted by a narrow temperature range due to enzyme protein denaturation. Moreover, the high cost of enzymes and their limited use in some organic solvents can be a restriction for the utilization of biocatalysts (
Khan and Rathod, 2015
; 
Pérez et al., 2017
; 
Zheng et al., 2015
).

In general, the SEs and the unreacted sucrose is precipitated with hexane or acetone. The solid obtained (complex mixed of mono and polysubstituted SEs) is solubilized in methanol and purified by liquid chromatography using chloroform, ethyl acetate, methanol, water, among others. Applying this approach, SEs with different degree of substitution can be isolated, however, a mixture of regioisomers are obtained from each SEs (
Becerra et al., 2008
; 
Crucho et al., 2008
; 
Pedersen et al., 2003
).

Before the identification and characterization of natural and synthetic sucrose esters by gas chromatographic techniques (GC) coupled with MS is the hydrolysis or derivatization of the samples prior analysis due to the relative low volatility of carbohydrates (
Karrer and Herberg, 1992
; 
Ruiz-Matute et al., 2011
).

Standard mono- and bi-dimensional NMR experiments have been used for the identification and structural elucidation of SEs and NSEs. Also, the NMR analyses may provide a detailed overview of the organic acid substituted on the sucrose moiety, as well as, the regiochemistry (
El-Rokh et al., 2018
; 
Mora Vargas et al., 2020
; 
Zhang et al., 2016a
).

The identification of SEs and NSEs with long-chain fatty acids as substituents such as lauric, capric, myristic, caprylic acid, among others (
Huang et al., 2010
; 
Pérez-Castorena et al., 2012
; 
Pérez et al., 2017
; 
Plat and Linhardt, 2001
; 
Zhu et al., 2009
) can be done by mono-dimensional NMR. It is observed that is a shift in the range of 0.3–3.0 ppm and 10–30 ppm for 
1
H
and 
13
C
NMR, respectively. The δ of the hydrogen atoms present on the -(
CH
2
) 
n-
group and the 
CH
3
− terminal of all long-chain fatty acid are observed at approximately 1.29–1.30 ppm (singlet, (s)) and approximately 0.90 ppm (triplet (t)), respectively. Also, the δ of the carbon atom on the carboxylic group is observed at approximately 172–175 ppm (
Bernal et al., 2018
; 
Huang et al., 2010
; 
Li et al., 2008
; 
Zhang et al., 2017
).

After careful analysis of the chemical shifts observed when sucrose hydroxyls were esterified, the structural elucidation of synthetic or NSEs can only be done after the analysis of two-dimensional experiments such as homonuclear and heteronuclear correlation experiments (
Pérez-Castorena et al., 2012
; 
Zhao et al., 2013
).

Characteristic signals of the SEs can be observed by heteronuclear multiple-bond correlation spectroscopy (
HMBC
). The C-1- 

O

-C-2′ glycosidic bond of sucrose is observed by this analysis. In this case, the signal of the hydrogen on the anomeric carbon of the α- D-glucopyranose ring is correlated with the anomeric carbon of the β- D-fructofuranose. Also, the signals of the hydrogen atoms on the C-1′ and C-3′ correlate with C-2’ anomeric carbon. The hydrogen atoms on the carbon near the acylated hydroxyl group show a signal in HMBC spectral, with the carbon atom on the carboxylic group (
Maier et al., 2015
; 
Pérez-Castorena et al., 2012
; 
Sun et al., 2000
).

NSEs from 

P.solanaceus

were isolated from its fruit (
1–3
) (
Fig. 4
), with no physiological activity reported. These NSEs are characterized by the presence of lauric acid in the C-2 hydroxyl group (
Pérez-Castorena et al., 2012
). The presence of saturated acids as substituents suggest that these NSEs can be used as emulsifiers in food industries since they do not generate undesirable flavors, unlike the ones with unsaturated substituents (
Nakamura, 1999
).

NSEs with aliphatic substituents have been found in tobacco leaves (

Nicotiana tabacum

, 
Solanaceae
). In tobacco, these compounds are produced in the leaves through biosynthesis or secretion by the cells in the head of glandular trichomes, which also synthesizes diterpenoids in different amounts (
Lin and Wagner, 1994
; 
Sallaud et al., 2012
).

NSEs extracted from 

Nicotiana tabacum

may play an important role in plant growth regulation, and also provide tobacco flavor precursor to cigarettes (
Kandra and Wagner, 1988
; 
Wagner et al., 2004
). 
Severson et al. (1985)
described the first methodology to extract these NSEs, but subsequently, different studies have been reported (
Ding et al., 2006
; 
Huang et al., 2018
; 
Kandra and Wagner, 1988
; 
Zhu et al., 2013
). However, the structures of these NSEs remain unclear to date.

(
Kim et al., 2010
), 

Prunus
(
Yoshinari et al., 1990
)


and 
Polygala

(
Jiang et al., 2005
; 
Miyase et al., 1999
), among others. These substituents give NSEs the chemical properties that allow their use as possible candidate for treatment of tumors (
El-Rokh et al., 2018
), as antioxidants (
Maier et al., 2015
; 
Tian et al., 2004
), and for other biological activities (
Table 2
). The degree of substitution influences the biological properties attributed to each compound. For instance, phenylpropanoid NSEs with low degree of substitution have been shown to have anti-inflammatory properties (
Wang et al., 2003
). However, polysubstituted NSEs have been used for their antitumor activities, suggesting them as promising chemopreventive agents (
Zhao et al., 2014
).

Genera of plants of pharmacological interest such as 

Phyllanthus
spp (Phyllanthaceae)

are used as traditional medicine in different countries for their biological activity in the treatment of diseases such as malaria (
Tona et al., 1999
), hypertension, diabetes and jaundice (
Bharati et al., 2015
; 
Sarin et al., 2015
), and for their anti-inflammatory activity (
Chouhan and Singh, 2011
), among other benefits. The biological activity seen was attributed to phenylpropanoid poly-substituted NSEs like compound (
65
, 
Fig. 11
) isolated from the extract of the dried leaf of 

Phyllanthus niruri

which had an inhibitory action on HIV virus (
Qian-Cutrone et al., 1996
), opening up the window for further pharmacological studies.
